Solid priorities for fragile states
LONDON/MONROVIA/KIGALI – No country has been spared by the repercussions of COVID-19.
However, the world's most 'fragile' states face a particularly complex set of issues.
In fact, before the pandemic began, countries like Yemen, Sudan, Haiti, Sierra Leone, Myanmar, Afghanistan, Venezuela, and others were already grappling with poverty, conflicts, corruption, and ineffective public administration.
Today, these elements leave these countries poorly equipped to manage the COVID-19 crisis.
What each country needs to get through the pandemic is precisely what fragile states lack: an effective state apparatus capable of developing and implementing an action plan, an efficient police force to enforce rules, social programs that provide funds, supplies, and health services to treat infected people.
The state’s lack of resources is immediately felt in public health.
While Europe has 4,000 intensive care beds per million inhabitants, several African regions have only five per million inhabitants.
Mali has just three ventilators for the entire country.
An effective response also requires trust in the state’s intervention.
However, in addition to its lack of resources, the public administration of most fragile states does not enjoy much popular support.
In countries recovering from conflict or suffering from endemic corruption, many people will refrain from supporting the government even if it proves capable of governing.
A strong private sector is also an essential component of effective and robust states.
Citizens should be able to work to support their families, and the state should be able to collect tax revenues to help those who cannot.
However, in fragile states, the official economy is not sufficiently present to meet these needs.
Earlier in the crisis, there was hope that some fragile states would avoid the worst health consequences of COVID-19 due to their young demographic weight and geographical distance.
However, as co-presidents of the new Council on State Fragility, we must acknowledge that this was not the case.
In recent weeks, Sudan, South Sudan, Somalia, and Yemen have all had infection and mortality rates rivaling those of developed countries hit by the coronavirus first.
Worse still, the economic consequences of the pandemic will certainly be more significant for fragile states. These will not only result from national lockdowns but also from what is happening abroad.
Trade with countries like China has faltered, remittances from expatriates have fallen, basic commodity prices and oil revenues have collapsed, and deficits are accumulating.
Since fragile states rely heavily on imports for their food supply, there is growing talk of "hunger" and even "famine".
We should now understand that problems in less developed countries often become global issues in the form of massive migrations, criminal or terrorist organizations, or economic repercussions.
Given that half of the impoverished population will live in fragile states by 2030, these problems will continue to worsen.
This is why the Council on State Fragility has made it an absolute priority to draw attention to the specific challenges these countries must face.
The council, composed of former world leaders, ministers, diplomats, business personalities, academics, and development agency presidents, will combine cutting-edge research with meticulous political knowledge. Its aim is to guide national and international policymakers who will determine how fragile states navigate this crisis and address their broader and deeper issues.
Decentralization, adaptability, and the wise use of data will be essential.
For example, it is widely proven that targeted "local lockdowns" are often more appropriate than national lockdowns.
Such knowledge could prove crucial for fragile states.
However, we must act quickly before the critical phase of the pandemic in the West comes to an end and the sense of urgency dissipates.
We propose five recommendations.
Firstly, access to social protection must be simpler and faster.
Sometimes, this will mean universal eligibility rather than precise targeting.
Mobile phone networks should be used to collect information on immediate needs and to make small regular payments (although of limited duration).
Secondly, national food production should be encouraged.
For example, Sierra Leone, which grew rice, has become increasingly dependent in recent decades.
More generally, Africa accounts for 60% of the world's unused arable land.
Local food production initiatives must be rapidly deployed at a much larger scale.
Thirdly, as soon as vaccine production begins, the international community must ensure that fragile states are not excluded from the market by wealthier countries.
When the threat is a contagious pathogen, no country is safe unless all are safe.
We must advocate and accelerate the production of multiple vaccines to ensure rapid and widespread distribution.
Fourthly, small businesses in fragile states need immediate assistance.
As noted by the most involved financial institutions in international development; small enterprises in less developed countries are often neglected and suffer the detrimental effects of broader goals and rules (since it is easier to achieve a goal by investing in larger projects in larger economies).
However, it is precisely these small enterprises that require greater investments.
Finally, the G20 should do more to support heavily indebted fragile states that are forced to choose between paying foreign creditors or saving their populations.
It is planned that countries receiving bilateral development aid will have to repay around 40 billion dollars to private and public creditors this year alone.
To prevent this financial shock, we urge all G20 members to suspend accumulated debts not only until next year but also until the end of the crisis.
In addition, it is crucial that all fragile states obtain emergency financing to support their efforts to contain COVID-19 and mitigate its economic repercussions—especially countries that do not typically have access to World Bank or International Monetary Fund financing.
COVID-19 will exacerbate existing problems in all fragile states around the world.
However, if the international community reacts quickly, we can mitigate the worst impacts of the pandemic.
If there is one lesson to be learned from this crisis, it is that livelihoods and lives will be saved if we move faster than the virus.
